<TITLE> SQ Chy is polluting politics, says Qamrul </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, August 17 (bdnews24.com) - BNP lawmaker Salahuddin Quader Chowdhury is a "polluting" influence on national politics, state minister for law Qamrul Islam said on Tuesday. Islam, earlier in the week, in the wake of ill-received comments by the BNP leader ahead of National Mourning Day, had also said Chowdhury would be brought to justice over war crimes allegations. Long-standing allegations against Chowdhury of establishing a torture camp in 1971 at his Goods Hill residence in Chittagong, and of killing the owner of a local pharmacy, continue to circulate widely in the country. State minister for home Shamsul Haque Tuku, brought the allegations to the fore again last week, saying the government had evidence of Chowdhury's direct involvement in the killing of Nuton Chandra Singh, the owner of the pharmacy. Chowdhury, also currently embroiled in a furore of over his recent claim that the assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman and members of his family had been "inevitable", denouncing the ruling party's backlash against him over the assassination remark and the renewed war crimes allegations, hit back on Monday. Chowdhury, in an indirect reference, termed both the state ministers for home and law as "inexperienced". "New and inexperienced people are trying to teach me manners. I don't want to reply to their remarks," he had said. Qamrul Islam, in a further reaction on Tuesday, told reporters: "These black sheep are enough to pollute politics." "People like SQ Chowdhury should be expelled from politics," Qamrul said. He also said: "We have evidence of his war crime in 1971. He must be tried." Tk 10 crore suit filed against SQ Chy Meanwhile, a Tk 10 crore defamation suit was filed against Chowdhury at a Khulna court on Monday, after the comments on the killing of Sheikh Mujib. The suit was filed by additional government prosecutor Sultana Rahman Shilpi at around midday at the additional chief magistrates court. Magistrate Abu Shamim Azad requested the Khulna metropolitan magistrate, Swapan Kumar Sarkar, to conduct a judicial probe into the case. Shilpi said in her deposition that she had been "mentally wounded" by Chowdhury's comment, made on Aug 13. b
